Background¶

Welcome to my March Madness notebook! I hope you are able to take something interesting away from this, potentially even using this to build your very own bracket for March Madness.

The intersection between analytics and sports has always been a passion of mine for as long as I can remember, as is building a bracket come March every year. With 64 teams competing in a single elimination tournament, it can be incredibly daunting trying to pick who will be your champion, who will upset who, which top seed is going to bust, etc. It is no wonder why so many people turn to non-traditional methods for building their brackets - picking their favorite mascots, favorite team colors, or maybe throwing darts on a wall and see which team you hit. Often times, these methods seem to result in a fairly successful bracket! It goes to show how much luck there really is.

My approach is a little bit different. What if we can predict the winners of each matchup using computer algorithms? Will it result in achieving the elusive "perfect bracket"?

Data Preparation¶

At a high level, my approach is to use the regular season performance for a given team to predict how they will perform in the tournament that same season. Each season is treated separately due to the high turnover in most team's rosters from season to season. Particularly at the smaller programs, both players and coaches are frequently transferring out for various reasons.

The first step is to transform the game results into a "matchup" for both teams involved. Looking at the regular_results_detailed_m data frame, it is currently structured where each game played is listed only once in the data set with the winning team's stats and losing team's stats included. To make this into a useable format, this will be transformed into a format that has each game appearing twice in the dataset for Team 1 vs. Team 2 and also Team 2 vs. Team 1. In this way, every team will appear as a Team 1 in the dataset.

In addition to transforming the dataset into the new format, the below function will also create several new features that are not included in the original dataset but potentially important for prediction including:

  • Possessions
  • Offensive and Defensive Efficiency Ratings
  • Shooting Percentages
  • Win Margin

Here, we also create the categorical response variable "win" which is a 1 if Team 1 beats Team 2 and a zero if Team 2 beats Team 1.

In [11]:
def prepare_data_modified(df):
    ignore = ['WLoc']
    t1_df  = pd.DataFrame(columns = df.columns, data = copy.deepcopy(df.values))
    t1_df = (t1_df.set_index(ignore, append=True).
             astype(int).
             reset_index(ignore))

    t2_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = df.columns, data = copy.deepcopy(df.values))
    t2_df = (t2_df.set_index(ignore, append=True).
         astype(int).
         reset_index(ignore))

    t1_df.loc[t1_df['WLoc'] == 'H', 'WLoc'] = 'A'
    t2_df.loc[t2_df['WLoc'] == 'A', 'WLoc'] = 'H'
    t1_df.columns.values[0] = 'location'
    t2_df.columns.values[0] = 'location'         
    t1_df.columns = [x.replace('W','T1_').replace('L','T2_') for x in list(t1_df.columns)]
    t2_df.columns = [x.replace('L','T1_').replace('W','T2_') for x in list(t2_df.columns)]
    
    output = pd.concat([t1_df, t2_df]).sort_index().reset_index(drop=True)
    
    output["GameNumber"] = output.groupby(['Season', 'T1_TeamID'])['DayNum'].rank(method='dense', ascending=True)

    output['T1_Possessions'] = output['T1_FGA'] - output['T1_OR'] + output['T1_TO'] + (0.475 * output['T1_FTA'])
    output['T2_Possessions'] = output['T2_FGA'] - output['T2_OR'] + output['T2_TO'] + (0.475 * output['T2_FTA'])

    output['T1_OER'] = output['T1_Score'] / ( output['T1_FGA'] +  ((output['T1_FTA'] * 0.9)/2 + output['T1_TO']))
    output['T2_OER'] = output['T2_Score'] / ( output['T2_FGA'] +  ((output['T2_FTA'] * 0.9)/2 + output['T2_TO']))

    output['T1_DER'] = output['T2_Score'] / ( output['T2_FGA'] +  ((output['T2_FTA'] * 0.9)/2 + output['T2_TO']))
    output['T2_DER'] = output['T1_Score'] / ( output['T1_FGA'] +  ((output['T1_FTA'] * 0.9)/2 + output['T1_TO']))

    output['T1_PAPP'] = output['T1_Score']/output['T1_Possessions']
    output['T2_PAPP'] = output['T2_Score']/output['T2_Possessions']
    
    output["T1_FGPercent"] = output["T1_FGM"] /  output["T1_FGA"]
    output["T1_FG3Percent"] = output["T1_FGM3"] /  output["T1_FGA3"]

    output["T2_FGPercent"] = output["T2_FGM"] /  output["T2_FGA"]
    output["T2_FG3Percent"] = output["T2_FGM3"] /  output["T2_FGA3"]
    
    output['T1_winMargin'] = output['T1_Score'] - output['T2_Score']
    output['T2_winMargin'] = output['T2_Score'] - output['T1_Score']
    
    output['win'] = np.where(output['T1_Score'] > output['T2_Score'], 1, 0)
    
    output['T1_TeamID'] = output['T1_TeamID'].astype(str)
    output['T2_TeamID'] = output['T2_TeamID'].astype(str)
    output['Season'] = output['Season'].astype(str)

    return output

It looks like there is some missing data for the women's data, caused by the creation of the FG3 percent dimension. There are instances where a team did not take a single 3 point shot in the entire game. As a result, the FG3 percentage would cause a divide by 0 error when calculated, thus explaining why these fields have NaN. Because it is only a select few observations, I will drop these games to avoid any future issues.

Calculate Team Quality Rankings¶

Each year, all 64 teams are ranked into seeds 1 to 16 within each of the four regions where the best teams are seeded as a 1 and the worst a 16. There are 4 number one seeds, 4 number 2 seeds, etc. These seeds are certainly very predictive as the better seeds are more likely to go further, and many do use these in their models as a predictor. However, a major problem I have with them is by using them, we are at the mercy of the logic (and maybe bias) that the selection committee holds. As such, I have opted to not use these as a predictor and rely solely on team performance data points.

In its place, I am creating my own "ranking" for each team in our data set. Using logistic regression, I am fitting a model to each Team 1 vs Team 2 matchup with the response being whether Team 1 won or not. The coefficients from this model give insight into the quality of that team relative to all other teams in the dataset. This is quite powerful as the final coefficients in effect account for the quality of opponent played as well. Not all 30+ win teams are created equal, and this will take that into consideration.

In [20]:
def team_quality(data):
    results = []
    
    for i in list(set(data.Season.values)): 

        x_train = data[data.Season == i][['Season', 'T1_TeamID', 'T2_TeamID', 'win']]
        x_train = pd.concat([pd.get_dummies(x_train.T1_TeamID, prefix='T1_TeamID'), pd.get_dummies(x_train.T2_TeamID, prefix='T2_TeamID')], axis=1)
        y_train = data[data.Season == i]['win']  

        logisticRegr = LogisticRegression(fit_intercept = True, 
                                          penalty=None, 
                                         max_iter = 5000, 
                                         )
        logisticRegr.fit(x_train, y_train)


        # extracting parameters from glm
        quality = pd.DataFrame(logisticRegr.coef_).transpose()    
        quality['TeamID'] = pd.DataFrame(x_train.columns)
        quality.columns = ['beta','TeamID']

        quality['Season'] = str(i)
        # taking exp due to binomial model being used
        quality['quality'] = np.exp(quality['beta'])
        # only interested in glm parameters with T1_, as T2_ should be mirroring T1_ ones
        quality = quality.loc[quality.TeamID.str.contains('T1_')].reset_index(drop=True)
        quality['TeamID'] = quality['TeamID'].apply(lambda x: x[10:14]).astype(str)
        quality = quality[['TeamID', 'beta', 'Season', 'quality']]
    
        results.extend(quality.values.tolist())
        
    results = pd.DataFrame(results)
    results.columns = ['TeamID', 'beta', 'Season', 'quality']
    
    return results

Calculated an Adjusted Ranking for Each Box Score Metric¶

This year, I am experimenting with another new method. In the past, I have used the quality rankings above with average box score metrics across the entire season as the primary features in my models. For example, my predictors consisted of average points scored, average points against, average rebounds, etc.

The only problem I have with that is that this does not take into account the quality of opponents faced relative to all teams in college basketball. If a small school program consistently scores 80+ points against their opponents, that does not mean they will also score 80+ points against a much better opponent in the tournamnet.

Using a similar approach to caculating the team quality rankings, my independent variables are dummy variables for all teams in the dataset and my dependent variable is the box score metric I am trying to adjust for. A simple linear regression model is then fit to this data, and the coefficients from the model can then be used as a ranking of sorts for that metric relative to their peers, adjusted for the opponents.

The function below calculates per season the coefficients for each box score metric that is passed in.

In [24]:
def adjusted_rankings(data,dimension):
    results = []
    
    for i in list(set(data.Season.values)): 
        x_train = data[data.Season == i].reset_index(drop = True)
        x_train = pd.concat([pd.get_dummies(x_train.T1_TeamID, prefix='T1_TeamID'),pd.get_dummies(x_train.T2_TeamID, prefix='T2_TeamID')], axis=1).reset_index(drop = True) #, pd.get_dummies(x_train.T2_TeamID, prefix='T2_TeamID')
        y_train = data[data.Season == i][dimension].reset_index(drop = True)
        
        linearReg = sm.OLS(y_train, x_train).fit()

        coefficients = pd.DataFrame(linearReg.params).reset_index()
        
        coefficients.columns = ['TeamID', 'Coefficient']
        coefficients['Season'] = i

        coefficients['Coefficient'] = RobustScaler().fit_transform(coefficients[['Coefficient']])

        coefficients = coefficients[coefficients['TeamID'].str.contains("T1")]

        coefficients = coefficients.sort_values('Coefficient', ascending = False)
        coefficients['TeamID'] = coefficients['TeamID'].str.replace('T1_TeamID_', '')

        results.extend(coefficients.values.tolist())
        
    results = pd.DataFrame(results)
    if "T1" in dimension: 
        dim = dimension.replace('T1_', '')
        results.columns = ['TeamID', dim + '_Coef', 'Season']
    else: 
        dim = dimension.replace('T2_', '')
        results.columns = ['TeamID', dim + '_Against_Coef', 'Season']
    
    return results

def run_adjusted_rankings(dataset, dims):
    adjusted_results = []
    for i in tqdm(range(len(dims))):
        for k in ["T1_", "T2_"]: 
            r = adjusted_rankings(dataset, k+dims[i])
            adjusted_results.append(r)
                    
    ranks = reduce(lambda  left,right: pd.merge(left,right,on=['TeamID', 'Season'],
                                                   how='inner'), adjusted_results)
    ranks['TeamID'] = ranks['TeamID'].astype(str)
    ranks['Season'] = ranks['Season'].astype(str)
    
    return ranks

Comparing the top teams on an average points scored basis versus the adjusted points scored using my method, it is very clear why taking a simple average of a box score metric does not paint the whole picture.

In the 2023 season, teams like Toledo and Oral Roberts were top 5 in average points scored. Does that make them a top 5 offense in all of college basketball? I would argue no, considering the teams they play against are nowhere near the same quality from a defensive perspective as the teams that Gonazaga, Arizona, and similar teams faced.

On the other hand, we see a team like Marquette which ranked 15th in the nation on an average points scored basis in 2023. Using my adjusted rankings though, they are 7th overall.

Calculate Averages for each Offensive and Defensive Box Score Metric¶

Since this is the first year experimenting with the adjusted box score metric approach, I will also plan to replicate my past approach of using the average box score metrics (average points, average rebounds, etc.) as the primary predictors for the models. This will be used as a baseline to understand if the adjusted ranking method performs better than simply using average offensive/defense performance.

In [30]:
def AverageStats(main_team, sub_team, dataset):
    transformed_dataset = dataset.groupby(['Season', main_team + '_TeamID']).agg({sub_team + "_Score": ["mean"],
                                                                    sub_team + "_FGPercent": ["mean"],
                                                                    sub_team + "_FG3Percent": ["mean"],
                                                                   sub_team + "_FGA3": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_FTA": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_OR": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_DR": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_Ast": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_TO": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_Stl": ["mean"], 
                                                                   sub_team + "_PF": ["mean"],
                                                                   sub_team + "_Possessions": ["mean"],
                                                                   sub_team + "_winMargin": ["mean"]
                                                                  })
    if main_team != sub_team: 
        transformed_dataset.columns = ['_'.join(col).replace(sub_team, main_team + "_Opponent") for col in transformed_dataset.columns.values]
    else: 
        transformed_dataset.columns = ['_'.join(col).strip() for col in transformed_dataset.columns.values]
    transformed_dataset.reset_index(inplace = True)
    
    return transformed_dataset

Calculate the spread between Team 1 average performance versus Team 2 average performance¶

In addition to average for and average against box score metrics calculated previously, I am also interested in including the differences between Team 1 and Team 2 for a given metric. In other words, I will also calculate Team 1 average score versus Team 2 average score, Team 1 average rebounds vs Team 2 average rebounds, etc.

Some advanced models (ex. neural networks) can detect interactions between multiple variables. However, I am planning to stick to simpler tree based models that aren't always able to inherently pick up on these interactions.

In [43]:
def featureDifferences(data):
    data['Score_Dif'] = data['T1_Score_mean'] - data['T2_Score_mean']
    data['FGPerc_Dif'] = data['T1_FGPercent_mean'] - data['T2_FGPercent_mean']
    data['FG3Perc_Dif'] = data['T1_FG3Percent_mean'] - data['T2_FG3Percent_mean']
    data['FGA3_Dif'] = data['T1_FGA3_mean'] - data['T2_FGA3_mean']
    data['FTA_Dif'] = data['T1_FTA_mean'] - data['T2_FTA_mean']
    data['OR_Dif'] = data['T1_OR_mean'] - data['T2_OR_mean']
    data['DF_Dif'] = data['T1_DR_mean'] - data['T2_DR_mean']
    data['Ast_Dif'] = data['T1_Ast_mean'] - data['T2_Ast_mean']
    data['TO_Dif'] = data['T1_TO_mean'] - data['T2_TO_mean']
    data['Stl_Dif'] = data['T1_Stl_mean'] - data['T2_Stl_mean']
    data['PF_Dif'] = data['T1_PF_mean'] - data['T2_PF_mean']
    data['Possessions_Dif'] = data['T1_Possessions_mean'] - data['T2_Possessions_mean']
    data['WinMargin_Dif'] = data['T1_winMargin_mean'] - data['T2_winMargin_mean']
    
    data['T1_Score_OppDif'] = data['T1_Score_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_Score_mean']
    data['T1_FGPercent_OppDif'] = data['T1_FGPercent_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_FGPercent_mean']
    data['T1_FG3Percent_OppDif'] = data['T1_FG3Percent_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_FG3Percent_mean']
    data['T1_FGA3_OppDif'] = data['T1_FGA3_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_FGA3_mean']
    data['T1_FTA_OppDif'] = data['T1_FTA_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_FTA_mean']
    data['T1_OR_OppDif'] = data['T1_OR_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_OR_mean']
    data['T1_DR_OppDif'] = data['T1_DR_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_DR_mean']
    data['T1_Ast_OppDif'] = data['T1_Ast_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_Ast_mean']
    data['T1_TO_OppDif'] = data['T1_TO_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_TO_mean']
    data['T1_Stl_OppDif'] = data['T1_Stl_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_Stl_mean']
    data['T1_PF_OppDif'] = data['T1_PF_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_PF_mean']
    data['T1_Possessions_OppDif'] = data['T1_Possessions_mean'] - data['T2_Opponent_Possessions_mean']
    
    data['T2_Score_OppDif'] = data['T2_Score_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_Score_mean']
    data['T2_FGPercent_OppDif'] = data['T2_FGPercent_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_FGPercent_mean']
    data['T2_FG3Percent_OppDif'] = data['T2_FG3Percent_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_FG3Percent_mean']
    data['T2_FGA3_OppDif'] = data['T2_FGA3_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_FGA3_mean']
    data['T2_FTA_OppDif'] = data['T2_FTA_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_FTA_mean']
    data['T2_OR_OppDif'] = data['T2_OR_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_OR_mean']
    data['T2_DR_OppDif'] = data['T2_DR_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_DR_mean']
    data['T2_Ast_OppDif'] = data['T2_Ast_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_Ast_mean']
    data['T2_TO_OppDif'] = data['T2_TO_mean'] - data['T1_Opponent_TO_mean']

    return data

Model Building¶

Checking for Correlation in our Data¶

Before fitting any models to the data, I wanted to quickly check for any major collinearity issues.

As observed in the below charts, there certainly are some very highly correlated variables. However, understanding how a typical basketball game works, these relationships make sense and I am not surprised. For example:

  • Steals vs Turnovers: When Team 1 steals the ball from Team 2, Team 1 is credited with a steal and Team 2 is credited with a turnover. As such, it makes sense that the correlation value between Team 1 Steals and Team 1 Opponent Turnovers should be quite high.
  • Possessions vs Scoring: Similarly, we see a high correlation between possessions and score. This makes logical sense considering each possession is another chance to score. So the higher number of possessions a team can generate, the score will typically be higher.

I have decided not to drop any of these variables that show high correlation for a couple of reasons. First, from my understanding of the game of basketball, I recognize that while correlated with each other, each feature contributes unique information to different aspects of a team's performance and in turn, their likelihood to win the game. Some teams are going to be very efficient with their possessions, others will be inefficient. Dropping possessions, for example, because it is highly correlated with score, would not be wise in my opinion.

More importantly, I know going in that I will be using a type of model (decision tree based) that is "immune" to multicollinearity problems. On each split, the model will only split on one variable. Thus, it does not really matter in the end if there are highly correlated features, the model will only consider one of them for each split when building a tree. If I were going to model with a non-tree based algorithm, I would consider dropping several features.

Note: All below correlation heatmaps have been subsetted for only variables that exhibit a correlation value of 0.75 or greater to allow for the chart to be readable.

def xgb_hyperparameter_tuning(params): 
    space = params[0]
    X_train = params[1]
    y_train = params[2]
    X_test = params[3]
    y_test = params[4]
    
    model = xgb.XGBClassifier(n_estimators = space['n_estimators'], 
                              learning_rate = space['learning_rate'], 
                              max_depth = int(space['max_depth']), 
                              gamma = space['gamma'], 
                              reg_alpha = space['reg_alpha'], 
                              reg_lambda = space['reg_lambda'], 
                              min_child_weight=space['min_child_weight'], 
                              colsample_bytree=space['colsample_bytree'], 
                              early_stopping_rounds=50, 
                              eval_metric="logloss", 
                              seed = 2024,
                              use_label_encoder=False)
    evaluation = [(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test)]

    model.fit(X_train, y_train,
              eval_set=evaluation, 
              verbose=0)

    logLossTrain = sklearn.metrics.log_loss(y_train,model.predict_proba(X_train))
    logLossTest = sklearn.metrics.log_loss(y_test,model.predict_proba(X_test))

    #change the metric if you like
    return {'loss': logLossTest, 'status': STATUS_OK, 'model': model}

# Classifier:
def lightGBM_hyperparameter_tuning(params):
    space = params[0]
    X_train = params[1]
    y_train = params[2]
    X_test = params[3]
    y_test = params[4]
    
    model = lightgbm.LGBMClassifier(max_depth = int(space['max_depth']), 
                                    num_leaves = int(space['num_leaves']),
                                    learning_rate = space['learning_rate'], 
                                    reg_alpha = space['reg_alpha'],
                                    reg_lambda = space['reg_lambda'],
                                    min_child_weight=space['min_child_weight'],
                                    colsample_bytree=space['colsample_bytree'], 
                                               verbosity = [-1], 
                                    random_state = 2024
                                   )
    
    evaluation = [(X_train, y_train), ( X_test, y_test)]
    
    model.fit(X_train, y_train,
              eval_set=evaluation, 
              eval_metric="logloss",
             callbacks=[lightgbm.early_stopping(stopping_rounds= 50, verbose=0)])

    logLossTrain = sklearn.metrics.log_loss(y_train,model.predict_proba(X_train))
    logLossTest = sklearn.metrics.log_loss(y_test,model.predict_proba(X_test))

    #change the metric if you like
    return {'loss': logLossTest, 'status': STATUS_OK}

Final Model Performance Results¶

Looking at the below table, ensembling the methods proved to be worthless. It provided equivalent results while increasing the complexity and decreased the interpretability of the models. As such, I will not be using any ensemble method for my final predictions.

Overall, I am quite surprised at how much better the models perform for predicting Women's games compared to Men's. For women, I am able to achieve a logloss around 0.45 for women compared to a logloss closer to 0.60 for men.

A couple of other key observations:

  • Models built off of Adjusted Offensive/Defensive rankings performs significantly better than using only average offensive/defensive box score metrics.
  • Performance between XGBoost and LightGBM is fairly comparable. If anything, I would give the XGBoost a slight edge as it performed marginally better for both men and women, whil also overfitting ever so slightly less. I would feel confident in using either method, but for prediction purposes, I will continue forward with XGBoost.

One important note that you will see below is that I have introduced an element of simulation to my final output. The output of any model will simply be the predicted probability that Team 1 win's over Team 2. Although I trust my models to produce strong predictions, adding another layer of randomness will help produce even stronger output considering the randomness of the tournament itself.

def prepare_data(seeds, preds):
    # Function preparing the data for the simulation
    seed_dict = seeds.set_index('Seed')['TeamID'].to_dict()
    inverted_seed_dict = {value: key for key, value in seed_dict.items()}
    probas_dict = {}
    
    for teams, proba in zip(preds['ID'], preds['Pred']):
        team1, team2 = teams[1], teams[2]

        probas_dict.setdefault(team1, {})[team2] = proba
        probas_dict.setdefault(team2, {})[team1] = 1 - proba

    return seed_dict, inverted_seed_dict, probas_dict


def simulate(round_slots, seeds, inverted_seeds, probas, random_values, sim=True):
    '''
    Simulates each round of the tournament.

    Parameters:
    - round_slots: DataFrame containing information on who is playing in each round.
    - seeds (dict): Dictionary mapping seed values to team IDs.
    - inverted_seeds (dict): Dictionary mapping team IDs to seed values.
    - probas (dict): Dictionary containing matchup probabilities.
    - random_values (array-like): Array with precomputed random-values.
    - sim (boolean): Simulates match if True. Chooses team with higher probability as winner otherwise.

    Returns:
    - list: List with winning team IDs for each match.
    - list: List with corresponding slot names for each match.
    '''
    winners = []
    slots = []

    for slot, strong, weak, random_val in zip(round_slots.Slot, round_slots.StrongSeed, round_slots.WeakSeed, random_values):
        team1, team2 = seeds[strong], seeds[weak]

        # Get the probability of team_1 winning
        proba = probas[str(team1)][str(team2)]
            
        if sim:
            # Randomly determine the winner based on the probability
            winner = team1 if random_val < proba else team2
        else:
            # Determine the winner based on the higher probability
            winner = [team1, team2][np.argmax([proba, 1-proba])]
            
        # Append the winner and corresponding slot to the lists
        winners.append(winner)
        slots.append(slot)

        seeds[slot] = winner

    # Convert winners to original seeds using the inverted_seeds dictionary
    return [inverted_seeds[w] for w in winners], slots


def run_simulation(brackets=1, seeds=None, preds=None, round_slots=None, sim=True):
    '''
    Runs a simulation of bracket tournaments.

    Parameters:
    - brackets (int): Number of brackets to simulate.
    - seeds (pd.DataFrame): DataFrame containing seed information.
    - preds (pd.DataFrame): DataFrame containing prediction information for each match-up.
    - round_slots (pd.DataFrame): DataFrame containing information about the tournament rounds.
    - sim (boolean): Simulates matches if True. Chooses team with higher probability as winner otherwise.

    Returns:
    - pd.DataFrame: DataFrame with simulation results.
    '''
    # Get relevant data for the simulation
    seed_dict, inverted_seed_dict, probas_dict = prepare_data(seeds, preds)
    # Lists to store simulation results
    results = []
    bracket = []
    slots = []
    
    # Precompute random-values
    np.random.seed(2024)
    random_values = np.random.random(size=(brackets, len(round_slots)))

    # Iterate through the specified number of brackets
    for b in tqdm(range(1, brackets+1)):
        # Run single simulation
        r, s = simulate(round_slots, seed_dict, inverted_seed_dict, probas_dict, random_values[b-1], sim)
        
        # Update results
        results.extend(r)
        bracket.extend([b] * len(r))
        slots.extend(s)

    # Create final DataFrame
    result_df = pd.DataFrame({'Bracket': bracket, 'Slot': slots, 'Team': results})

    return result_df

def matchupGenerator(seeds_df):
    results = []
    
    for i in list(set(seeds_df.Season.values)): 
        
        matchups = list(itertools.combinations(np.array(seeds_df[seeds_df.Season == i].TeamID), 2))
        matchups = pd.DataFrame(matchups)
        matchups['Season'] = i
        matchups.columns = ['T1_TeamID', 'T2_TeamID', 'Season']

        matchups['IDLow'] = np.where(matchups['T1_TeamID'] < matchups['T2_TeamID'], matchups['T1_TeamID'], matchups['T2_TeamID'])
        matchups['IDHigh'] = np.where(matchups['T1_TeamID'] > matchups['T2_TeamID'], matchups['T1_TeamID'], matchups['T2_TeamID'])

        matchups['ID'] = matchups["Season"].astype(str) + '_' + matchups["IDLow"].astype(str) + '_' +matchups["IDHigh"].astype(str)
        matchups['T1_TeamID'] = matchups['IDLow'] #matchups['T1_TeamID'].astype(str)
        matchups['T2_TeamID'] = matchups['IDHigh'] #matchups['T2_TeamID'].astype(str)
        matchups.drop(['IDLow', 'IDHigh'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

        matchups['Season'] = matchups['Season'].astype(str)
            
        results.extend(matchups.values.tolist())
        
    results = pd.DataFrame(results)
    results.columns = ['T1_TeamID', 'T2_TeamID', 'Season', 'ID']

    return results

Mens 2024 Bracket Predictions¶

How should this be interpretted? Every "slot" is a game that will be played by a certain combination of teams. Each team only has one possible path to the championship, and their opponents are limited based on the structure/path of the other teams in the bracket.

Each slot has various predicted probabilities that correspond to the probability that team is the winner of that slot across all 100,000 simulated brackets. The team with the highest probability is the team we would build our bracket with as the winner for that slot. For example:

  • The R1 East 1 slot is the matchup between Connecticut and Stetson. Using our model, across 100,000 simulated brackets, Stetson is the winner in ~10% of them, and Connecticut is the winner ~90% of the time.
  • R2 East 2 is the matchup between the winner fo the R1 East 1 (#1 vs #16) slot and the R1 East 8 slot (#8 vs #9). Connecticut is the winner in ~71% of simulated brackets, Florida Atlantic is the winner in ~11% of simulated brackets, Northwestern is the winner in ~14% of simulated brackets, and Stetson is the winner in only ~3% of simulated brackets.

The "R1" games are all pretty self explanatory, they correspond to each of the 8 games played within each region/division of the tournament.

  • R1 East 1 slot is the game played between the East #1 seed and the #16 seed.
  • R1 East 2 slot is the game played between the East #2 seed and the #15 seed.
  • Etc.

"R2" slots correspond to the second round of the tournament, also known as the round of 32, where each division has 4 games played. The way the brackets are built, the top seeds will play winner of the highest game slot from the previous round.

  • R2 East 1 slot is the matchup between the winner of R1 East 1 and R1 East 8.
  • R2 East 2 slot is the matchup between the winner of R1 East 2 and R1 East 7.
  • Etc.

"R3" slots correspond to the third round of the tournament, also known as the Sweet Sixteen where each division has 2 games played. Similar to the previous logic, the winner of the top slot in R2 will play the winner of the worst slot in R2 as the R3 matchup.

  • R3 East 1 slot is the matchup between R2 East 1 and R2 East 4.
  • R3 East 2 slot is the matchup between R2 East 2 and R2 East 3.

"R4" slots correspond to the fourth round of the tournament, also known as the Elite 8 where each division has 1 games played. Similar to the previous logic, the winner of the top slot in R3 will play the winner of the worst slot in R3 as the R4 matchup.

  • R4 East 1 slot is the matchup between R3 East 1 and R3 East 2.

"R5" slots correspond to the fifth round of the tournament, also known as the Final Four. This round comprises of the final team in each division. In 2024, this is the matchup between the East champion and the West Champion, and the matchup between the South Champion and the Midwest champion.

"R6" is the final championship game.

Men's bracket built off of the above simulation:¶

Scoring:

  • Round 1 = 23/32 correct
  • Round 2 = 11/16 correct
  • Round 3 = 3 / 8 correct
  • Round 4 = 2 / 4 correct
  • Round 5 = 2 / 2 correct
  • Round 6 = 0 / 1 correct

Following ESPN's scoring system of:

  • Round 1 = 10 points per correct
  • Round 2 = 20 points per correct
  • Round 3 = 40 points per correct
  • Round 4 = 80 points per correct
  • Round 5 = 160 points per correct
  • Round 6 = 320 points per correct

Total score of: 230 + 220 + 120 + 160 + 320 + 0 = 1050

It wasn't until the Elite 8, round 3, where my bracket truly was "busted". It was still a respectable end result, and would have even been better if Purdue won the championship. The model gave Purdue just the slight edge over UConn. It would have won my office bracket pool at least!

Final Thoughts¶

When it comes to predicting how the March Madness tournament will unfold for both the Men's and Women's tournament, everyone has their methods. Some pick the higher seeds, some pick based off of colors, others their favorite mascot. Considering all typically result in a respectable bracket, it is evident that there is a lot of luck involved.

The purpose of this notebook is to have some fun trying a new methodology at building brackets. It was far from perfect, but nobody has ever predicted the entire tournament perfectly. However, when we remove our biases and let the mathematics determine the better teams, I think we might have a chance to get there. With a little bit of luck.
